          <tr><td><strong>Commercial Rent</strong></td><td>$14-20/sq ft annually</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Current Dispensaries</strong></td><td>3-4 (moderate)</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Why Brunswick?</h2>
      <p>Brunswick is the largest community in mid-coast Maine, with approximately 20,000 residents within town limits. The greater Brunswick area — including Topsham and Harpswell — adds another 15,000-20,000 people to the regional market. This is not a small town. It is the commercial and cultural hub for a significant swath of coastal Maine.</p>
      <p>The town's economic foundation is unusually diversified for its size. Healthcare is the largest employer, anchored by Mid Coast Hospital and its associated physician practices and outpatient facilities. Manufacturing persists in certain niches. But the most distinctive economic feature is Bowdoin College — a selective liberal arts college that brings 1,800 students and hundreds of faculty and staff into the community each year.</p>
      <p>Bowdoin is not just an employer. It shapes the character of the town in ways that matter for dispensary operators. The college brings a young, educated, generally progressive demographic to Brunswick. These customers tend to be cannabis-friendly, open to trying new products, and willing to pay for quality. They also tend to be price-conscious in the way that students are — looking for value rather than luxury, but willing to spend when they perceive genuine quality.</p>
      <p>Brunswick's location on I-295 and Route 1 makes it accessible from both Portland (35 miles south) and the more rural communities of western and northern Maine. Customers from Bath, Topsham, Lisbon, and even parts of Lewiston may find Brunswick more convenient than Portland for their dispensary visits.</p>
    </section>

    <Callout title="The Bowdoin Factor" type="info">
      Bowdoin College brings a young, educated, cannabis-friendly demographic to Brunswick. Students and faculty tend to be early adopters. They care about product quality and are willing to pay for it. But unlike purely tourist-driven markets, this demographic creates stable, year-round demand. College terms create predictable traffic patterns. Parents visiting during Orientation, Family Weekend, and graduation create occasional spikes. The college calendar becomes your operational calendar.
    </Callout>

    <section>
      <h2>Market Data</h2>
      <table aria-label="Brunswick dispensary market data" caption="Market demographics and competitive landscape for Brunswick Maine dispensary opportunity">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Factor</th><th>Assessment</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>City Population</td><td>20,000+</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Regional Market</td><td>35,000-40,000 (including Topsham, Harpswell)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>College</td><td>Bowdoin College (1,800 students, 300 faculty)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Competition</td><td>Moderate (3-4 dispensaries)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Primary Access</td><td>Route 1, I-295, US Business 1</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Median Household Income</td><td>$58,000-62,000 (above Maine average)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Key Demographics</td><td>Healthcare workers, college community, local families</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The Bowdoin Opportunity</h2>
      <p>Bowdoin College students and faculty are a distinct customer segment that shapes the entire Brunswick market. They skew younger than the general population. They are generally progressive on cannabis issues and arrive at college already familiar with legal cannabis from states where it is more widely available. They tend to value quality over price, but they are also students — so value matters.</p>
      <p>This demographic is not as seasonal as tourist-driven markets. College terms create predictable traffic patterns. The fall semester brings returning students and new first-years in September. Parents arrive for Orientation in late August and Family Weekend in October. Spring graduation in May creates another spike. These predictable patterns allow for staffing and inventory planning that purely seasonal businesses cannot match.</p>
      <p>The college connection also affects product preferences. Students tend to favor concentrates, edibles, and portable vaporizer products over traditional flower. They often have limited storage space in dorm rooms and shared apartments. Faculty and staff tend to be more conventional in their purchasing but appreciate product education and variety.</p>
      <p>Position your dispensary as a quality-focused operation. Emphasize product knowledge, strain variety, and a welcoming atmosphere. The Brunswick customer — particularly the college-affiliated customer — will research your menu before visiting. They will read reviews. They will ask their friends. Your reputation among this demographic travels fast.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Brunswick's Competitive Landscape</h2>
      <p>Three to four dispensaries currently operate in the Brunswick area. This is moderate competition — not saturated like Portland, but not wide open like some rural markets. The existing dispensaries have established customer bases, but the market is not so crowded that new entrants cannot find positioning room.</p>
      <p>Brunswick's geographic position matters for understanding competition. It sits between Portland (35 miles south) and Lewiston-Auburn (30 miles northwest), both of which have more dispensaries per capita. Some Brunswick customers may drive to Portland for selection or price — but many prefer the shorter trip to Brunswick, particularly for quick top-ups or when they know exactly what they want.</p>
      <p>The Brunswick dispensaries that have succeeded focus on what the local community values: consistency, product knowledge, and community connection. The Bowdoin demographic in particular values being recognized and treated as individuals rather than transactions. A dispensary that knows its regulars, remembers preferences, and creates genuine community connection earns loyalty that pure product selection cannot match.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Local Rules and Licensing</h2>
      <p>Brunswick requires both a Maine OCP Adult-Use Retail License and local approval from the Town of Brunswick. The local approval process involves review by the Planning Board, which evaluates site plan compliance, parking, signage, and neighborhood impact. Brunswick has been generally supportive of cannabis businesses but maintains standards around location and operational characteristics.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>State License:</strong> OCP Adult-Use Retail License from Maine's Office of Cannabis Policy</li>
        <li><strong>Local Approval:</strong> Site plan review and conditional use approval from Brunswick Planning Board</li>
        <li><strong>Local Annual Fee:</strong> $2,500 paid to the Town of Brunswick</li>
        <li><strong>School Buffer:</strong> 500-foot minimum from schools (Morse High School, Brunswick Junior High, elementary schools)</li>
        <li><strong>Zoning:</strong> Commercial and Village Center zones — residential zones prohibited</li>
        <li><strong>Security:</strong> Must meet Maine OCP requirements including surveillance and access-controlled storage</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The Brunswick Planning Board typically meets on the first and third Thursdays of each month. Applications must be submitted at least three weeks before a meeting to be placed on the agenda. The town has a professional planning staff that works constructively with applicants, though site plan review can take 60-90 days from submission to approval.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Best Locations in Brunswick</h2>
      <p>Brunswick's commercial geography divides into three distinct zones, each serving different customer bases and offering different tradeoffs.</p>
      <table aria-label="Brunswick recommended dispensary locations" caption="Recommended areas and rent benchmarks for Brunswick dispensary locations">
