    <section>
      <h2>Real Estate Considerations</h2>
      <p>Brunswick has three primary commercial zones worth considering for dispensary location. Each offers different tradeoffs between visibility, rent, parking, and customer demographics.</p>
      <p>Maine Street in downtown Brunswick is the historic heart of the community. It attracts locals, college visitors, and tourists who come for the independent bookstores, restaurants, and galleries that line the street. The Bowdoin College campus is within easy walking distance. Foot traffic is genuine but not as heavy as a highway corridor. Rent for commercial space on Maine Street runs $16-20 per square foot annually, reflecting the downtown character and college proximity.</p>
      <p>Cook's Corner is the suburban shopping area near the Brunswick Mall, off Route 24. This area has a more typical suburban retail feel — ample parking, chain retailers, and customers who drive rather than walk. Rent is notably lower here, $14-17 per square foot, and the customer base skews toward families and older residents. This is a good location for operators who want to serve the general local population without the college-centric positioning.</p>
      <p>Route 1 runs the length of the town and catches regional traffic from surrounding communities. Customers from Bath, Topsham, Lisbon, and even parts of Woolwich regularly drive through Brunswick on Route 1. This is the highway access play — lower rent (typically $12-15 per square foot) but more car-dependent customer patterns. A dispensary here relies more on visibility and signage to capture passing trade.</p>
      <p>Square footage for a dispensary typically runs 1,200-1,800 square feet, including retail floor, budroom, security vault, and storage. The 500-foot school buffer affects certain parcels near Morse High School on Morse Street and the Brunswick Junior High on Industry Road. Verify your chosen location against school district maps before committing to a lease.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>What Makes Brunswick Different</h2>
      <p>Brunswick is not a tourist destination in the way Kittery or Portland are. Your customer base is primarily local — residents who will visit repeatedly, who talk to their neighbors, who write Google reviews and tell their friends. That changes how you should think about marketing and customer retention fundamentally.</p>
      <p>A dispensary in Brunswick lives or dies on reputation within the local community. One bad experience spreads by word of mouth with surprising speed. One memorable, positive experience does too. Invest in making every customer feel known and respected. Reward loyalty with recognition or a simple punch-card program. Train your budtenders to remember regulars and their preferences. In a town of 20,000 people, being known as the dispensary that treats people right is a genuine competitive advantage.</p>
      <p>The Bowdoin College connection matters beyond just student customers. Faculty and staff often have higher disposable income than students. They are community leaders — teachers, doctors, nonprofit directors, local business owners. If your dispensary earns their trust and respect, their endorsements carry weight throughout the community. This is the long game: build genuine connections with the college-affiliated segment, and the entire local network benefits from their recommendations over time.</p>
      <p>Brunswick's stability is an underrated advantage. Unlike tourist-dependent markets that see dramatic seasonal swings, Brunswick's customer base is present year-round. The college calendar provides predictability. Healthcare workers provide steady employment. The local economy does not boom and bust dramatically. For operators who prefer planning with reasonable confidence to gambling on tourist surges, Brunswick offers a different kind of opportunity.</p>
    </section>

